  }, "This is not happening any time soon."), "\n  "), mdx("h2", null, "Am I fluent?"), mdx("p", null, "The most common question I get when I tell people I\u2019m learning Japanese is, \"Are\nyou fluent?\" It seems like a fair question to ask, especially given the amount\nof time I\u2019ve spent on it. A quick Google search for \"how long does it take to be\nfluent in a language\" will give top answers in the range of 200 to 720 hours.\nSo, given I\u2019ve spent 1,328 hours studying Japanese, surely I should be fluent\nmany times over now, right?"), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "No.")), mdx("p", null, "I have dedicated the next few paragraphs to explain why this isn\u2019t the case.\nHopefully, this will set expectations for new learners and more importantly,\nprove to myself that I\u2019m not a horrendously slow learner."), mdx("h3", null, "What is fluency?"), mdx("p", null, "It\u2019s time to question the question. 'Fluency' is quite an abstract concept and\nopen to very different interpretations. Firstly, there\u2019s the question of which\nskills you need to acquire to say you\u2019re fluent. For example, you might think\n'fluency' only refers to your ability to verbally communicate . This makes sense\nbecause for a long time the majority of the population were illiterate but were\nstill viewed as 'fluent' in their native language. On the other hand, not\nknowing how to read or write in your target language does feel a bit incomplete.\nThere are also other aspects to communicating successfully beyond language, such\nas gestures and cultural etiquette."), mdx("p", null, "Secondly, there\u2019s the question of what mastery you need attain to be classed as\n'fluent'. Conversational fluency, in which you are able to converse on everyday\ntopics (with room for mistakes), is a far cry from being able to eloquently\nexpress yourself on a range of complex topics."), mdx("p", null, "I would argue that the term 'fluency' isn\u2019t a very helpful term for measuring\nlanguage acquistion at all. It\u2019s too ambiguous and highly contextual. You might\nhave a near faultless exchange with a native speaker about the weather, which\nconvinces them that you\u2019re fluent. But that evening, the waiter at a restaurant\ngives you an English menu after seeing the panic on your face trying to decipher\nJapanese text. In these situations, being perceived as 'fluent' is a fleeting\nstate that you can attain or lose depending on the context and who you\u2019re with."), mdx("p", null, "When I think about how I\u2019m progressing with Japanese, I always compare my\nJapanese with my English. This does set unachievable standards for acquiring\nJapanese. I already have 25 years of practice with English and still use it more\nfrequently than I do Japanese. So it\u2019s unlikely my Japanese will ever surpass my\nEnglish. However, setting the bar at where my native language stands does make\nmy North Star a lot less ambiguous. It also exposes the sheer amount of time\nlearning a new language takes, which is often glossed over or outright\nfabricated by marketers trying to sell you something."), mdx("p", null, "In the end, I can feel good about reading a book in Japanese or having a\nconversation with my mum but I don\u2019t delude myself into thinking, \"That\u2019s it! I\nhave mastered the language now.\" If I had tried to read the same sorts of things\nI do in English, such as technical books, or talk about the same sorts of things\nI do in English, such as philosophy or politics, I wouldn\u2019t know where to start.\nEven writing this same blog post in Japanese seems like an impossible feat or at\nleast, would take me several more years."), mdx("p", null, "So I guess a better answer to the question, \"Are you fluent?\" is, \"It depends.\""), mdx("h2", null, "What else have I learned?"), mdx("p", null, "One of the interesting things I have found about the past year is that I haven\u2019t\njust learned Japanese. I have also developed a lot of other skills as a\nby-product."), mdx("h3", null, "Resilience"), mdx("p", null, "It\u2019s worth saying that I picked up learning Japanese during the pandemic and I\ntruly believe it\u2019s what helped me not only get through it and but have one of\nthe best years I have ever had. Someone recently said to me that developing\nresilience is a lot about having a clear direction of where you want to go, even\nin the midst of chaos. And that really spoke to what learning Japanese has given\nme. I had clear long term goals of what I wanted to achieve from the outset and\nI have, luckily, been able to focus on that even as the world fell apart around\nme."), mdx("h3", null, "Time management"), mdx("p", null, "My time management and discipline is way better than I ever thought it could be.\nI have been spending pretty much most of my free time studying, more than I ever\ndid at university (when I didn\u2019t even have a job to distract me). One of the\nthings that helped me was using my timer app to time each study session. The app\ngives you a superficial rank depending on how much time you\u2019ve clocked in during\nthe week. As trivial as it sounds, the idea of gaining or losing a rank often\npushed me to study, even on days when I was more reluctant to do so."), mdx("h3", null, "Enjoyment"), mdx("p", null, "To my surprise, I found that I actually enjoy studying Japanese and the slow\ngrind to get marginally better at the language every day. At the beginning, I\nset my sights on the end goal, getting good at Japanese, and never considered\nthat I would enjoy the journey itself. In particular, I\u2019ve really enjoyed\ngamifying the learning process and tracking my progress across various metrics.\nI also love that I am able to peep into another world and consume untranslated\nmaterials, like news articles and books, that are inaccessible to most of the\nworld\u2019s population."), mdx("span", {
